{"id":74,"date":"2023-07-26T09:33:02","date_gmt":"2023-07-26T09:33:02","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/thaodean.com\/?p=74"},"modified":"2023-07-26T09:51:16","modified_gmt":"2023-07-26T09:51:16","slug":"serving-your-wordpress-site-as-static-files-with-rust-and-kubernetes","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/thaodean.com\/sw\/serving-your-wordpress-site-as-static-files-with-rust-and-kubernetes\/","title":{"rendered":"Serving Your WordPress Site as Static Files with Rust and Kubernetes"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>In today&#8217;s fast-moving world, website performance and security are critical. One interesting way to maximize these aspects is by serving your WordPress site as static files, updated daily, with a Rust server running on Kubernetes. In this article, we&#8217;ll explore the benefits, challenges, and steps involved in this process.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Why Static Files?<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Static websites offer several advantages. They load faster than dynamic sites because there&#8217;s no server-side processing, leading to better user experience and improved SEO. Static sites also have a smaller attack surface area, improving security. Furthermore, once generated, static sites are easy to serve and can be efficiently handled by Content Delivery Networks (CDNs), making scalability easier to achieve.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Why Rust and Kubernetes?<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Rust is a modern system programming language that offers safety, concurrency, and performance. It&#8217;s an excellent choice for building a server thanks to its low resource usage and high speed. Kubernetes, on the other hand, is a platform for automating deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications. It provides a robust foundation for deploying our Rust server.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Generating Static Pages<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>To turn our WordPress site into a static one, we can use a WordPress plugin like Simply Static, WP2Static, or Static HTML Output. These plugins generate a static version of your site, which can then be exported to a location where your Rust binary can access it.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Serving Static Pages with Rust<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Our Rust application will be responsible for serving the static files. We can use the <code>warp<\/code> library for this purpose, creating a simple script to serve files in a specific directory.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Dockerizing and Deploying with Kubernetes<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>For deployment, we&#8217;ll use a distroless Docker image, which includes only our application and its runtime dependencies. Using a multi-stage Docker build, the first stage builds the Rust binary, and the second stage copies the Rust binary into a distroless base image.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We can then deploy this Docker image to Kubernetes, taking advantage of its powerful features for managing our server pods.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overcoming Limitations<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>While static sites offer various benefits, they also come with some limitations. For example, updates on the WordPress site won&#8217;t immediately reflect on the live site until the next update cycle. Dynamic features such as user comments or e-commerce functionalities may be limited or require extra work to implement on static sites.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To handle e-commerce functionality, we can integrate third-party solutions like Snipcart, Shopify&#8217;s Buy Button, or Ecwid. For any other dynamic behavior, we can use serverless functions or API endpoints.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Serving your WordPress site as static files using a Rust server on Kubernetes can significantly improve your site&#8217;s performance and security. Although the setup might be complex, and there might be limitations to overcome, the benefits can make it a worthwhile approach for many WordPress site owners. Be sure to consider your specific needs and the trade-offs before deciding if this strategy is right for you.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>In today&#8217;s fast-moving world, website performance and security are critical. One interesting way to maximize these aspects is by serving your WordPress site as static files, updated daily, with a Rust server running on Kubernetes. In this article, we&#8217;ll explore&#8230; <a class=\"more-link\" href=\"https:\/\/thaodean.com\/sw\/serving-your-wordpress-site-as-static-files-with-rust-and-kubernetes\/\">Continue Reading &rarr;<\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[14,11],"tags":[],"acf":[],"jetpack_featured_media_url":"","jetpack-related-posts":[{"id":40,"url":"https:\/\/thaodean.com\/kubernetes\/to-kubernetes-or-not-making-the-decision-for-your-personal-project\/","url_meta":{"origin":74,"position":0},"title":"To Kubernetes or Not: Making the Decision for Your Personal Project","author":"thaodean","date":"07\/22\/2023","format":false,"excerpt":"Are you planning a personal project and pondering whether Kubernetes is the right choice? Deciding on an orchestration platform can be a challenging task, especially when you have to choose between convenience and control, ease of use and complexity. This article will guide you through key considerations, helping you decide\u2026","rel":"","context":"In &quot;Kubernetes&quot;","block_context":{"text":"Kubernetes","link":"https:\/\/thaodean.com\/category\/kubernetes\/"},"img":{"alt_text":"","src":"","width":0,"height":0},"classes":[]},{"id":135,"url":"https:\/\/thaodean.com\/sw\/aws\/title-hosting-a-static-website-on-aws-with-amazon-s3-and-route-53\/","url_meta":{"origin":74,"position":1},"title":"Hosting a Static Website on AWS with Amazon S3 and Route 53","author":"thaodean","date":"08\/01\/2023","format":false,"exce